  "datePublished": "2026-03-04",
  "description": "Tagging on the web emerged from the convergence of two older practices: library subject indexing (where trained catalogers applied terms from a controlled vocabulary to classify materials) and informal annotation (where individuals labeled their own files and bookmarks for personal retrieval). The web\u0026rsquo;s contribution was making tagging social, collaborative, and visible — turning private labels into shared discovery infrastructure.\n¶Social bookmarking and the birth of folksonomies (2003-2005) The modern tagging era began with del.icio.us, a social bookmarking service launched by Joshua Schachter in 2003. Users saved web bookmarks and applied free-text tags to organize them. Because bookmarks were shared, the same URL could be tagged by thousands of users independently, producing what Thomas Vander Wal named a folksonomy in 2004 — a taxonomy that emerged from the \u0026ldquo;folk\u0026rdquo; rather than from experts. Flickr, launched the same year, extended tagging to photographs, making unsearchable visual content findable through text. These early systems demonstrated that free tagging at scale could produce useful organizational structure without central planning, but they also revealed the characteristic weaknesses of uncontrolled vocabularies: synonym fragmentation, inconsistent granularity, and tag spam.\n",
  "name": "history of tagging on the web",
